Understanding NullReferenceException in C#

To truly understand why a NullReferenceException occurs, we first need to look under the hood at how C# handles data in memory.
In C#, data types are fundamentally divided into two main categories:

1. Value Types : int, double, bool, char.

Value types hold their data directly in memory. When you create a value type, 
it always contains a value and cannot be empty.

2. Reference Types : class, string, array, interface.

Reference types do not store the actual data directly.
they store a reference pointing to where the data is actually kept

What is null?

If you declare a variable of a Reference Type but you do not assign it a place in memory
the default value of that variable is null. In programming, null means "nothingness" or "no object exists here."
It essentially means your variable is acting as a blank address tag that isn't pointing to anything.

The Anatomy of a NullReferenceException

A NullReferenceException is thrown when you try to access a member (like a method, property, or field)
of a reference type variable that is currently null.

// 1. We create a reference variable named 'name', but we point it to nothing (null).
string name = null;

// 2. BOOM! A NullReferenceException is thrown exactly here.
Console.WriteLine(name.Length);
